ly Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Dorset): habitational name from Dowland in Devon, possibly named from Old English <i>dūfe</i> ‘dove’ + <i>land</i> ‘open country’. The name is pronounced with the first element rhyming with <i>owl</i>, but it may have been confused with and absorbed by <b>Dolling</b>, also a Devon name (see   Dollins  ). The name may also be a post-medieval variant of <b>Dolling</b> (see   Dollins  ), with shortening of <i>-ing</i> to /ən/, as in   Dowlen  , to which excrescent <i>-d</i> was added at will.","Irish: probably a variant of   Dowlin   or   Dolan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dollins","meanings":["English (Somerset): variant of <b>Dollin</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, itself a variant of <b>Dolling</b>, a nickname from an unrecorded Middle English <i>dolling</i>, <i>douling</i>, <i>dulling</i> ‘dull or stupid one’ (compare   Doll  ). The name may also have arisen from a late assimilation of <i>rl</i> to <i>ll</i> in <i>Dorling</i>, a variant of   Darling  . Compare   Dollens  ."]},{"name":"Doland","meanings":["English: unexplained. Some examples of the modern surname may belong with   Dowland  .","Irish: from <b>Ó Dubhláin</b>, see   Dolan  ."]}]},{"name":"Florence","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval form of the Latin masculine name <i>Florentius</i> (a derivative of <i>florens</i> ‘blossoming, flourishing’) and its feminine form <i>Florentia</i>. In the Middle Ages the name was commonly borne by men (as, for example, the historian Florence of Worcester), but it is now exclusively a girl's name. This was revived in the second half of the 19th century, being given in honour of  Florence Nightingale  (  1820–1910 ), the founder of modern nursing, who organized a group of nurses to serve in the Crimean War. She herself received the name because she was born in the Italian city of Florence (Latin <i>Florentia</i>, Italian <i>Firenze</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Florance","meanings":["Medieval form of the Latin masculine name <i>Florentius</i> (a derivative of <i>florens</i> ‘blossoming, flourishing’) and its feminine form <i>Florentia</i>. In the Middle Ages the name was commonly borne by men (as, for example, the historian Florence of Worcester), but it is now exclusively a girl's name. This was revived in the second half of the 19th century, being given in honour of  Florence Nightingale  (  1820–1910 ), the founder of modern nursing, who organized a group of nurses to serve in the Crimean War. She herself received the name because she was born in the Italian city of Florence (Latin <i>Florentia</i>, Italian <i>Firenze</i>)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Florence Dowsland was born in 1232, in Bywell, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom. She married Thomas Lawesson about 1258. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1310, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 78."},"et":{"1232–1310":"1232–1310","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","about 1260":"umbes 1260","1310":"1310","1232":"1232","about 1258":"umbes 1258","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bywell, Northumberland, England":"Bywell, Northumberland, England"},"fi":{"1232–1310":"1232–1310","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1260–Male":"1260–Kuollut","about 1260":"noin 1260","1310":"1310","1232":"1232","about 1258":"noin 1258","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bywell, Northumberland, England":"Bywell, Northumberland, England"},"fr":{"1232–1310":"1232–1310","1240–Male":"1240–Décédé","1260–Male":"1260–Décédé","about 1260":"environ 1260","1310":"1310","1232":"1232","about 1258":"environ 1258","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Bywell, Northumberland, England":"Bywell, Northumberland, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Florence Dowsland est née en 1232, à Bywell, Northumberland, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a é